@node "intro" "Introduction"
@smartwrap


@{u}Introduction@{uu}


Napster is an MP3 sharing community using a special client that features
things like chatting, searching, downloading, notify lists, etc. If you
want to read more about Napster in general, go to http://www.napster.com.
Here you can also download the official Windows version of the client.


Amster is an Open Source MUI based Napster client for AmigaOS.


@{u}Trademark and copyright notices@{uu}


Amiga, AmigaOS and Workbench are trademarks of Amiga, Inc.

Napster is a trademark of Napster, Inc.

Windows® is a registered trademark of Microsoft Corporation

@{"MUI" link "mui"} is copyright © Stefan Stuntz

@endnode

@node "license" "License"
@smartwrap


@{u}License@{uu}


Amster (Amiga Napster client)

Copyright © 1999-2000 Gürer Özen

Copyright © 2000 Jacob Laursen


Amster is released under GPL. You can find a copy of GPL at
http://www.gnu.org/copyleft/gpl.html


No reverse engineering on Napster client was done to make this client,
it's fully based on protocol documentation by the Linux community.

@endnode

@node "require" "Requirements"
@smartwrap


@{u}Requirements@{uu}


* AmigaOS 3.x

* MUI 3.8 or higher

* NList.mcc 19.97+ (MUI Class)

* TCP/IP stack (Genesis, Miami 2.0+ or MiamiDx)


Amster will also use Lamp.mcc 11.1+ if available. TWFmultiLED 12.6+
will be used if chosen in prefs or Lamp.mcc 11.1+ is not available.
Neither of these classes are required to run Amster.


@{u}For recompiling sources@{uu}


* SAS/C 6.50+           Commercial

* MUI Developer Kit     Aminet, dev/mui/mui38dev.lha

* Miami Developer Kit   http://www.nordicglobal.com

* FlexCat               Aminet, dev/misc/FlexCat.lha

* OpenURL includes      Aminet, comm/www/OpenURL30.lha

* Lamp.mcc includes     Aminet, dev/mui/MCC_Lamp.lha

* NList.mcc includes    Aminet, dev/mui/MCC_NList0_89.lha

* TWFmultiLE includes   Aminet, dev/mui/MCC_TWFmultiLE.lha

@endnode

@node "install" "Installation"
@smartwrap


@{u}Installation@{uu}


Double-click on the Install icon and the installer script will guide you
through the installation.


Amster keep its preferences in ENVARC: (Amster.prefs).


When upgrading from pre-0.7 versions, please note:


- Amster.default is now called Amster.shares.

- The last three sound/script events needs reconfiguration.

@endnode

@node "faq" "FAQ"

@{u}FAQ@{uu}

Q. I can't find same MP3's after reconnecting?
A. Napster has many MP3 servers, and they're not linked together. If you
   enable "Cache servers" in the configuration (Options/Server list), you
   can find the same server using the navigator window (from the Amster
   menu).

Q. Amster exits with "cannot create mui app!" message.
A. Check your MUI installation and make sure you have a reasonable amount
   of RAM available.

Q. When creating my own account and logging in for the first time,
   I get "Invalid password" from server.
A. Username is already taken - try another.

Q. When starting Amster, I get the error "Failed to open main window!".
A. If you're running a very low resolution, this may be the problem.
   Solution: Increase the screen size. When you've done that you can save
   some space by disabling the icon panel (from the Settings menu).

Q. Amster sucks. Are there any other Napster clients for Amiga?
A. Yes, aNapster (http://www.crosswinds.net/~jsiv/anapster) and the BWap
   port, which can be found on Aminet.

@endnode

@node "mainwin" "Main window"
@smartwrap


@{u}Main window@{uu}


This is the window that you'll see when starting Amster. It consists of
three parts:


@{u}1. Searching@{uu}


@{b}Song@{ub}


Enter the keywords you want to search for here. They can be part of the
song title, the artist or both. Each keyword must be seperated with a
space. Press return to perform the file search.


@{b}Max.@{ub}


Maximum number of hits to return to the result list. This may be any
number from 3 to 100. (Default is 100)


@{b}Advanced search options@{ub}


Press the little @{"popup" link "adv-search"} gadget right next to the "Max." string gadget to
see these options. The popup is typically pictured as a magnifying glass.


@{b}Search@{ub}


Perform the file search based on the above mentioned criterias.


@{b}User / Browse button@{ub}


This will list all MP3 files shared by a single user. The list is shown
when you press return or the browse button. Please note that the search
criterias are ignored when gathering this list!


@{b}Result list@{ub}


The '@' to the left indicates link speed intervals (only available when
Lamp.mcc or TWFmultiLED is installed):


Black  = Unknown

Red    = Modem

Yellow = ISDN/cable

Green  = DSL/T1+


If the time is shown in italics, it's because the time calculation by
Amster and the sharing client differs more than 3%. This may be due to a
huge ID3v2 tag or simply a bug in the other client.


@{b}Clear / Clear all@{ub}


Remove all or selected search results from the list. "Clear all" is only
useful when "Clear list before new searches" is disabled in the
configuration (@{"Options" link "conf-opts"}).


@{b}Download@{ub}


@{"Download" link "download"} selected file(s). You can also double-click
on a file to download it.


@{b}Paths@{ub}


If selected, full paths will be shown in the result list.


@{u}2. Connection panel@{uu}


@{b}Status line@{ub}


This contains information about number of shared songs on the server and
how many gigabytes that is. It will automatically update every now and
then. The lamp to the right indicates connection status: green = online,
yellow = connected, red = offline, black = lost/no connection.


@{b}Connect@{ub}


This will get the optimal server from the main server and then connect to
it. If you have configured an MP3 server, you will connect directly to
this one.


@{b}Disconnect@{ub}


Disconnects you from the server.


@{b}Reconnect@{ub}


If you have configured a main server, pressing this button will
disconnect, reconnect and find a new optimal server. This will usually
connect you to a new server with other users and files. So if you didn't
find what you searched for, reconnect.


@{u}3. Icon panel@{uu}


@{b}Info@{ub}


Open/close a @{"debug window" link "info"}. Here you can see a log of
events, such as established or failed connections and welcome messages.


@{b}Messenger@{ub}


Open @{"chat window" link "messenger"} - chat not fully implemented yet.


@{b}Multi-chat@{ub}


Open a new @{"channel window" link "chat"}.


@{b}Download@{ub}


Open/close @{"download window" link "download"}.


@{b}Sharing@{ub}


Open/close @{"library window" link "sharing"}.


@{b}Config@{ub}


Open/close @{"configuration window" link "config"}.

@endnode

@node "adv-search" "Advanced search options"
@smartwrap


@{b}Line speed must be...@{ub}


If "Not important" is selected in the first cycle gadget, this search
option is ignored. Otherwise you build a criteria with the two cycle
gadgets, like this:


"Line speed must be" + "At Least" + "ISDN 64K"


This statement will only give you results with line speed equal to or
higher than 64 kbps.


@{b}Bitrate must be...@{ub}


This will decrease the number of search results by demanding a certain
bitrate in the MP3 encoding. It works the same way as the "Line Speed must
be..." option.


@{b}Frequency must be...@{ub}


Like the other two advanced search options.

@endnode

@node "info" "Debug window"
@smartwrap


@{u}Debug window@{uu}


This window will gather information returned by the server, and debug
information. This information is more verbose than the information
displayed in the status line in the main window. When filing in bug
@{"reports" link "bugreport"}, please include details from this window.


@{b}Clear@{ub}


Press this button the clear the window contents.

@endnode

@node "messenger" "Messenger window"
@smartwrap


@{u}Messenger window@{uu}


From this window you can communicate with other users. Available commands
at the moment:


 <nick> <message>


to send a message to another user. And:


 /whois <nick>


to get userinfo from another user.

@endnode

@node "chat" "Amster Chat"
@smartwrap


@{u}Chat window@{uu}


You can open as many chat windows as you like. In each window you can join
a chat channel, just like when using IRC. The available commands are:


 /list


to get a list of available channels on the server. A new window will pop
up with the list.


 /join <channel>


to join the channel.


 /leave


to leave the channel in that window.

@endnode

@node "download" "Download window"
@smartwrap


@{u}Download window@{uu}


This window contains a list of all downloads.


The four buttons have the following meaning:


@{b}Play@{ub}    - Spawns external MP3 player - this is configured in the

          @{"Events section" link "conf-events"}. It's possible to spawn the player before

          the download is finished. If your Internet connection is fast

          enough, you can listen to music while you download it!


@{b}Abort@{ub}   - Cancel download of the selected file.


@{b}Resume@{ub}  - Start the transfer of the selected file again. A resume requester

          will show up asking you if you want to proceed.


@{b}Cleanup@{ub} - This will remove all finished/aborted downloads from the list.



@{u}Resume@{uu}


If the file to download already exists in your download directory, a
resume requester will show up with some of the following choices
(depending on an MD5 checksum comparison, which will be shown in the
requester):


@{b}Resume@{ub}    - Continue download of the existing file.

@{b}Rename@{ub}    - Download the file with a new file name.

@{b}Overwrite@{ub} - Overwrite the existing file.

@{b}Cancel@{ub}    - Cancel the download.


The MD5 checksum and filesize of incomplete files are saved in the file
comment. Tip: If you find a file you want to resume, you can rename your
existing file to the same name, before proceeding. If the MD5's do not
match, but you are sure it's the same file (or are willing to take the
chance, based on filesize comparison), you can simply delete the file
comment, which will reduce Amster's resume denial to a resume warning.


@{u}Errors@{uu}


Unfortunately every download will probably not proceed as planned. Here's
a list of some of the possible errors and their meaning:


@{b}Logged out@{ub} - The user logged out and the requested file is no longer

             available


@{b}Teaser@{ub}     - The user sharing the file currently has a queue

             limit of 0, which means that nobody can download

             from the user at the moment.


@{b}Busy@{ub}       - The user is currently busy serving other users, and

             you ran out of @{"retries" link "conf-adv"}.


@{b}Timed out@{ub}  - The download was caught by Amsters garbage collector,

             because the request wasn't fulfilled within 2 minutes, and

             thus considered timed out. Use "Resume" to try again.

@endnode

@node "upload" "Upload window"
@smartwrap


@{u}Upload window@{uu}


This window contains a list of all uploads.


The two buttons have the following meaning:


@{b}Abort@{ub}   - Cancel upload of the selected file.


@{b}Cleanup@{ub} - This will remove all finished/aborted uploads from the list.

@endnode

@node "sharing" "File sharing"
@smartwrap


@{u}Library window@{uu}


Here you can add/remove files to your library of shared files. The library
will always be synchronized with the server, so there's no need to
speculate about updating it manually. You can drag'n'drop files into this
window to add them.


@{b}The buttons@{ub}


 Add           - Add files to your library.

 Add recursive - Add files recursively. A requester will ask for the

                 directory from which to start the recursion.

 Remove        - Remove selected files from your library.

 Remove all    - Remove all files from your library.


@{b}The library menu@{ub}


 Load...    - Load another library.

 Save       - Save current library in currently used file

              (default is "Amster.shares").

 Save as... - Save current library in another file.


Don't forget to save your library - this is not done automatically, unless
you have "Auto-save library on program exit" enabled in the configuration
(@{"Options" link "conf-opts"}).

@endnode

@node "config" "Configuration"

@{u}Configuration@{uu}

  @{" User            " link "conf-user"}  - User account information
  @{" Options         " link "conf-opts"}  - Amster options
  @{" Events          " link "conf-events"}  - Program events
  @{" Advanced        " link "conf-adv"}  - Advanced configuration

@endnode

@node "conf-user" "User settings"
@smartwrap


If you haven't registered a Napster account yet, just enter your user data
in this section and connect.


@{u}Username@{uu}


This must be a unique username. If you get a "wrong password" error when
trying to connect, the username is probably already taken. Solution: Try
another one.


@{u}Password@{uu}


Don't forget to save the configuration and/or write down your password.


@{u}E-Mail@{uu}


Enter your e-mail address here.


   @{b}Update@{ub} - Click here to update your e-mail address on the server.

            You must be connected to a server to perform this operation.

            Note: This feature is not implemented in the Napster servers

            yet!


@{u}Connection@{uu}


Select your kind of Internet connection here. It's shown when other users
/whois you and when showing your shared files.


@{u}Download path@{uu}


All downloaded files will be saved in this directory.


@{u}Filename length@{uu}


All filenames exceeding this limit will be truncated and have the ".mp3"
postfix appended. For FFS set this to 30, for PFS2 to 31 and for PFS3/SFS
to 100.

@endnode

@node "conf-opts" "Program options"
@smartwrap


@{u}Auto-connect on program startup@{uu}


If this option is enabled, Amster will automatically connect to the
Napster server when the program is started. Otherwise you'll manually have
to press the 'Connect' button in the main window.


@{u}Clear list before new searches@{uu}


When performing new searches, Amster can either accumulate the displayed
results or clear the list each time. Enable this option if you want the
latter.


@{u}Always ask filename@{uu}


Enable this to always have a file requester pop up before downloading a
file. This way you'll have a chance to rename the file in a meaningful way
instead of letting Amster truncate the name automatically.


@{u}Add downloaded files to library@{uu}


Automatically add downloaded files to your shared library.


@{u}Auto-save library on program exit@{uu}


Automatically (and silently) save sharing library on program exit (will
only write the file if it has changed).


@{u}Auto-cleanup successful uploads@{uu}


Automatically remove uploads from the @{"upload window" link "upload"} once they're
successfully transfered.


@{u}Server list@{uu}


This list is shown when you open the navigator window.


   @{b}Don't remember@{ub} - Don't save the list to a file when quiting Amster.


   @{b}Save on exit@{ub}   - Save the server list on program exit.


   @{b}Cache servers@{ub}  - Automatically add new servers to the list. This includes

                    servers returned by the meta server and servers you

                    manually type in. When this option is enabled, the list

                    will automatically be saved on program exit.


@{u}Lamps@{uu}


Select which MUI lamp class you wish to use. You will have to restart
Amster for this to have effect.

@endnode

@node "conf-events" "Program events"
@smartwrap


@{u}Events@{uu}


In this section you can define what Amster should do when one of the
listed events occur:


Startup

Exit

Connect

Disconnect

Download finished

Upload finished

Transfer error


For each event you can select a sound file to play. Make sure you have a
datatype installed for playing your sound files. And for the last event:


MP3 player


you can select an AmigaDOS command to run when 'Play' is pressed in the
@{"download window" link "download"}. Example scripts are included in the
Rexx/ directory for spawning some of the most popular MP3 players for
AmigaOS.


%f is replaced with the filename, so normally you will have to add "%f" to
your player command or script. Example:


RexxC:RX Rexx/PlayAmigaAmp.rexx "%f"

@endnode

@node "conf-adv" "Advanced settings"
@smartwrap


@{u}Meta server@{uu}


This is the server Amster will connect to in the first place to get the
address of the optimal Napster server. Default is server.napster.com:8875.
Each time Amster connects to this server, it is most likely to receive a
different server address than last time. Don't mess around with the meta
server address unless you know what you're doing.


@{u}MP3 server@{uu}


If you write anything here, Amster will attempt to connect directly to
this server, instead of getting the optimal server from the main server
first. Usually you don't want to do that.


@{u}Listening port / Behind firewall@{uu}


Enter a port number you want to use for the sharing server here. If you're
behind a firewall and can't allow connections to any ports, select this
option. Note: Not used yet!


@{u}Concurrent downloads / Pri@{uu}


Maximum number of simultaneous downloads. The rest will be queued and
downloaded later. Pri sets set task priority.


@{u}Concurrent uploads / Pri@{uu}


Maximum number of simultaneous uploads. The rest will be rejected. Pri
sets the task priority.


@{u}Queue limit retries / Delay between retries@{uu}


Number of times to attempt to download a queued file. The delay is the
number of seconds between each attempt. Don't set this too low, or you
might get kicked or banned from the server.

@endnode

@node "arexx" "Available ARexx commands"

Name of ARexx port: AMSTER.<x> where x is the instance number of the
program.

@{b}CONNECT@{ub}

 Syntax:    CONNECT

 Function:  Connects to a server (the same as pressing the "Online" button).

 Result:    RC = 0  -  All OK


@{b}DISCONNECT@{ub}

 Syntax:    DISCONNECT

 Function:  Disconnects from a server (the same as pressing the "Offline"
            button).

 Result:    RC = 0  -  All OK


@{b}DOWNLOAD@{ub}

 Syntax:    DOWNLOAD NUM/A/N

 Function:  Download song.

 Input:     NUM - song number (returned by the SEARCH command).

 Result:    RC = 0  -  All OK
            RC = 9  -  No such number in list
            RC = 10 -  Not online


@{b}ISONLINE@{ub}

 Syntax:    ISONLINE

 Function:  Check if Amster is currently online.

 Result:    RC = 0  -  Offline
            RC = 1  -  Online.


@{b}SEARCH@{ub}

 Syntax:    SEARCH TITLE/A,STEM/A

 Function:  Searches for a song.

            Please note that this command doesn't work correctly when
            "Clear list before new searches" is disabled.

 Input:     TITLE - Song title or artist
            STEM  - The STEM to contain the results

 Result:    RC = 0  -  All OK
            RC = 10 -  Failure
            RC = 15 -  Not connected and logged in

            <STEM>.COUNT             Number of search results
            <STEM>.<NUM>.TITLE       Song title
            <STEM>.<NUM>.USER        User name
            <STEM>.<NUM>.MD5         MD5 checksum
            <STEM>.<NUM>.SIZE        File size
            <STEM>.<NUM>.BITRATE     Bitrate
            <STEM>.<NUM>.FREQUENCY   Frequency
            <STEM>.<NUM>.TIME        Time in seconds
            <STEM>.<NUM>.LINK        Link: 0 = Unknown
                                           1 = 14.400 Modem
                                           2 = 28.800 Modem
                                           3 = 33.600 Modem
                                           4 = 56K Modem
                                           5 = ISDN 64K
                                           6 = ISDN 128K
                                           7 = Cable
                                           8 = DSL
                                           9 = T1
                                          10 = T3+


@{b}SEARCHSTATE@{ub}

 Syntax:    SEARCHSTATE

 Function:  Check if Amster is currently searching.

 Result:    RC = 0  -  No search started.
            RC = 1  -  Amster is currently searching
            RC = 2  -  Amster has the results


@{b}WHOIS@{ub}

 Syntax:    WHOIS USER/A

 Function:  Shows the userinfo in the messenger window.

 Result:    RC = 0  -  All OK

@endnode

@node "history" "Past versions"

@{u}History@{uu}

0.7a
----
* Improved ARexx SEARCH command
* A few bugfixes (for details, see file CHANGES)


0.7
----
* Channel list window
* Hotlist
* Improved messenger/chatter
* More flexible transfer manager
* Lots of bugfixes


0.6
----
* Upload (sharing)
* Built-in server navigator
* Automatic download retry when other client is busy
* Transfer queue settings
* Filename truncation with .mp3 suffix
* Improved error handling
* Lots of bugfixes and minor improvements


0.5a
-----
* List sorting in main- and share window
* Chat - EXPERIMENTAL
* Misc. small bugfixes and changes


0.5
----
* Resume support
* New network code
* Threaded downloads
* Improved GUI
* Player support
* /whois command (in messenger window)
* File share window (uploads not implemented yet)
* Now saves search options in config
* A few ARexx commands
* More languages


0.4
----
* Amster.guide
* Locale support
* Advanced search criterias
* Reconnect button
* Browse a specific user's files
* New configuration options
* New menus
* Shared file access


0.3
----
* Info/debug window
* Option to clear result list automatically
* Chat


0.2
----
* Version spoofing


0.1
----
* Initial public release

@endnode

